  <h2>The question</h2>
  <p>
    HR teams routinely discover attrition risk too late — after an employee has mentally checked out, or started interviewing elsewhere. The typical response is reactive: exit interviews that confirm what was already visible in the data. The goal here was to flip that: use behavioural and compensation signals to flag risk 60–90 days before it becomes a resignation, with an explainable model HR managers could act on without a data science degree.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p><strong>The hard constraint:</strong> Most attrition models are riddled with data leakage. Features that are only observable <em>after</em> someone decides to leave (e.g. reduced performance ratings, reduced training activity) get included in training — the model looks great in validation but fails in production. I solved this with a strict point-in-time split: training features are only those observable at a fixed snapshot date, with no lookahead.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>The approach</h2>

  <h3>Data engineering (BigQuery + dbt)</h3>
  <p>
    Built a dbt project with three layers — <strong>staging</strong> (clean source tables from the HR system), <strong>intermediate</strong> (point-in-time feature construction, compensation history, tenure calculations), and <strong>marts</strong> (model-ready features + prediction outputs). 75 dbt tests enforce schema contracts, row-count expectations, and referential integrity — so a broken upstream table fails loudly before it corrupts the model.
  </p>

  <h3>ML model (scikit-learn + SHAP)</h3>
  <p>
    Trained a logistic regression with SHAP explainability — deliberately interpretable over a black-box ensemble, because HR managers need to understand <em>why</em> someone is flagged before they'll act on it. The point-in-time split ensures no feature is derived from post-decision data.
  </p>

