  <h2>What broke / what I'd change</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Feature engineering was the hardest part, not the model.</strong> Getting a clean point-in-time view without lookahead required careful thought about which fields in the HR system are updated retroactively (several are). The dbt intermediate layer exists almost entirely to solve this.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Precision@top-10% is the right metric, not AUC.</strong> HR teams act on a shortlist — they're not going to review every flagged employee. Optimising for the top decile of predictions (Precision@10%) reflects how the model is actually used. I should have framed evaluation this way from day one instead of defaulting to AUC first.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Next iteration:</strong> add time-series features (change in tenure trajectory, rolling compensation delta) and experiment with a gradient boosting model. The interpretability cost is manageable with SHAP waterfalls even for tree ensembles.
  </p>

